(15, 1, 'Non-Married Couples: Establish Paternity / Child Custody / Child Support', 'No', NULL, NULL, 'https://player.vimeo.com/video/920104564', '<p>Hello and welcome to YourBestLawyer.com. Establishing paternity, child custody, and child support for unmarried couples involves a legal process designed to ensure that the rights and responsibilities of both parents are formally recognized and that the best interests of the child are protected.</p> <p><strong>PATERNITY</strong></p> <p>Establishing paternity is a foundational step in cases involving unmarried couples who share a child. It is the process of legally confirming the biological father of the child. Paternity can be established either voluntarily through a signed acknowledgment by both parents or involuntarily through a court process. Generally, the court will order the parents to cooperate with genetic testing if there is a dispute or uncertainty about the child\'s parentage. Once paternity is legally established, it grants both parents certain parental rights and obligations concerning the child.</p> <p><strong>CHILD CUSTODY</strong></p> <p>When there are minor children involved, the court typically issues orders related to child custody. This is done to ensure the well-being of the children while safeguarding the parental rights of both parents. Custody matters are inherently delicate, given that the impact of a separation on children can manifest in various ways, often resulting in emotional, economic, and social consequences.</p> <p>Consequently, when negotiating custody arrangements in Arizona, two fundamental aspects are addressed: legal decision-making and parenting time. Legal decision-making involves the right to make crucial decisions regarding children, such as those related to medical, education, and religious upbringing. This authority can be either granted solely to one parent, referred to as sole legal decision-making, or granted jointly to both parents, known as joint legal decision-making.</p> <p>With respect to parenting time, formerly known as visitation, pertains to the children’s schedule of time spent with each parent. Depending on the negotiations your attorney is able to work out for you, the court will determine a parenting time schedule, including holidays and vacation time, which is determined to be in the children’s best interests. The Court may award equal parenting time or may award one parent more time than the other depending on the circumstances. The specific allocation of time spent with each parent will be outlined in the court\'s ruling.</p> <p>The court\'s custody determinations in Arizona are guided by numerous factors, with the paramount consideration being the best interests of the children. According to Arizona Revised Statute 25-403, several key considerations must be considered during this process:</p> <p>First, the past, present, and potential future relationship between the parent and the child is a crucial factor. Additionally, the interaction and interrelationship of the child with their parents, siblings, and other significant individuals affecting the child\'s best interests are evaluated. The child\'s adjustment to their home, school, and community is also taken into consideration.</p> <p>Furthermore, if the child is of a suitable age and maturity, their wishes regarding legal decision-making and parenting time are considered. The mental and physical health of all individuals involved, along with the likelihood of a parent allowing the child frequent, meaningful, and continuing contact with the other parent, is assessed. However, this consideration does not apply if the court determines that a parent is acting in good faith to protect the child from witnessing or being a victim of domestic violence or child abuse.</p> <p>Other factors include whether one parent intentionally misled the court, whether there has been domestic violence or child abuse, the nature and extent of coercion or duress used by a parent, compliance with relevant legal provisions, and any conviction of false reporting of child abuse or neglect.</p> <p>In contested legal decision-making or parenting time cases, the court is mandated to make specific findings on the record regarding all relevant factors and the reasons justifying the decision in the best interests of the child.</p> <p><strong>CHILD SUPPORT</strong></p> <p>In Arizona, child support is determined through the Arizona Child Support Guidelines, which utilizes a formula using several key factors.</p> <p>The factors include the gross income of both parents, the amount of parenting time of each parent, the number of children for whom support is being calculated and whether they are over 12 years of age, costs for childcare, health insurance premiums, the number of other children the parents have a legal obligation to support and/or other child support obligations actually being paid by the parents as well as extraordinary expenses associated with special needs and/or gifted children.</p> <p>Adjustments may apply if the combined gross income exceeds a certain threshold or due to unique circumstances. It\'s essential to recognize that the specific child support amount can vary based on individual situations, with the court using these guidelines as a foundation.</p> <p>Courts can deviate from the Guidelines if it\'s deemed to be in the child\'s best interests. Child support orders are subject to modification in the event of a significant change in circumstances such as income, parenting time, or the child\'s needs.</p>\n<p><strong>LEGAL FEES</strong></p> <p>Legal fees can be covered through three distinct methods. First, a flat fee arrangement is commonly employed in criminal law cases. Second, a contingency fee structure is often utilized for personal injury cases, where the attorney\'s compensation is a pre-negotiated percentage derived from the client\'s settlement.</p> <p>However, in family law and other civil matters, a prevailing approach involves 