vised Statute 25-403, several key considerations must be considered during this process:</p>\n<ul>\n    <li>First, the past, present, and potential future relationship between the parent and the child is a crucial factor. Additionally, the interaction and interrelationship of the child with their parents, siblings, and other significant individuals affecting the child\'s best interests are evaluated. The child\'s adjustment to their home, school, and community is also taken into consideration.</li>\n    <li>Furthermore, if the child is of a suitable age and maturity, their wishes regarding legal decision-making and parenting time are considered. The mental and physical health of all individuals involved, along with the likelihood of a parent allowing the child frequent, meaningful, and continuing contact with the other parent, is assessed. However, this consideration does not apply if the court determines that a parent is acting in good faith to protect the child from witnessing or being a victim of domestic violence or child abuse.</li>\n    <li>Other factors include whether one parent intentionally misled the court, whether there has been domestic violence or child abuse, the nature and extent of coercion or duress used by a parent, compliance with relevant legal provisions, and any conviction of false reporting of child abuse or neglect.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>In contested legal decision-making or parenting time cases, the court is mandated to make specific findings on the record regarding all relevant factors and the reasons justifying the decision in the best interests of the child.</p>\n\n<p><strong>CHILD SUPPORT</strong></p>\n<p>In Arizona, child support is determined through the Arizona Child Support Guidelines, which utilizes a formula using several key factors.</p>\n<p>The factors include the gross income of both parents, the amount of parenting time of each parent, the number of children for whom support is being calculated and whether they are over 12 years of 